\begin{align*}
g(4) &= 3(4) + 5 \\
&= 12 + 5 \\
&= 17.
\end{align*}
Similarly, we have:
\begin{align*}
f(4) &= 4 + 3 \\
&= 7.
\end{align*}

Now we can calculate $f(g(4))$ and $g(f(4))$. We have:
\begin{align*}
f(g(4)) &= f(17) \\
&= 17 + 3 \\
&= 20.
\end{align*}
Similarly, we have:
\begin{align*}
g(f(4)) &= g(7) \\
&= 3(7) + 5 \\
&= 21 + 5 \\
&= 26.
\end{align*}

Finally, we can calculate $f(g(4))-g(f(4))$. We have:
\begin{align*}
f(g(4)) - g(f(4)) &= 20 - 26 \\
&= -6.
\end{align*}
