In a paired comparison experiment comparing version 1 and version 2 of a software tool, we observed that customers preferred version 1 35% of the time and version 2 65% of the time. Why was a 95% prediction interval larger than a 99% prediction interval?
A 95% prediction interval is wider than a 99% prediction interval because it provides a more conservative estimate of the range of possible values for the next observation. This is due to the fact that a 95% prediction interval is wider to account for more of the uncertainty in the data. In contrast, a 99% prediction interval is more precise but less likely to contain the true value, as it takes into account less uncertainty. The larger the confidence level, the wider the prediction interval will be, ensuring a higher probability that the interval will contain the true value of the next observation.

Solve the following system of linear equations:
\[
\begin{cases}
-21x - 10y = 19 \\
4x + 23y = -8
\end{cases}
\]
To solve the system of equations, we can use Gaussian elimination. First, we write the augmented matrix:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc|c}
-21 & -10 & 19 \\
4 & 23 & -8
\end{array}
\right)
\]

Now, we perform row operations to get the matrix in row echelon form:

1. Add $\frac{4}{21}$ times row 1 to row 2:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc|c}
-21 & -10 & 19 \\
0 & \frac{493}{21} & \frac{38}{21}
\end{array}
\right)
\]

2. Multiply row 2 by $\frac{21}{493}$:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc|c}
-21 & -10 & 19 \\
0 & 1 & \frac{38}{493}
\end{array}
\right)
\]

3. Add 10 times row 2 to row 1:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc|c}
-21 & 0 & \frac{9617}{493} \\
0 & 1 & \frac{38}{493}
\end{array}
\right)
\]

4. Divide row 1 by -21:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 0 & -\frac{458}{493} \\
0 & 1 & \frac{38}{493}
\end{array}
\right)
\]

The solution to the system is:
\[
\begin{align*}
x &= -\frac{458}{493} \\
y &= \frac{38}{493}
\end{align*}
\]

